    "title": "The Advanced Passive 1: Perfect Passives",
    "description": "Using passive voice with present and past perfect tenses for official research results.",
    "display_order": 22,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-21"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# The Advanced Passive 1: Perfect Passives\n\nIn university reports, we often use the **Present Perfect Passive** to talk about research that is finished and important for the present. We also use the **Past Perfect Passive** to talk about something finished in the deep past.\n\n### 1. Present Perfect Passive\nUse this to report results that are still important today.\n- **Formula**: have / has + **been** + **V3**.\n- **Example**: The data **has been analyzed**. (Focus is on the data, not the person.)\n- **Example**: Thousands of students **have been registered**.\n\n### 2. Past Perfect Passive\nUse this for an object that was changed **before** another past action.\n- **Formula**: **had** + **been** + **V3**.\n- **Example**: The building **had been opened** before the storm arrived.\n\n### 3. Difference: Active vs. Passive\n- **Active**: The scientist has analyzed the results. (Scientist is focus.)\n- **Passive**: The results **have been analyzed** by the scientist. (Results are focus!)\n\n### 4. Common Verbs\n- do \u2192 **done**\n- write \u2192 **written**\n- analyze \u2192 **analyzed**\n- conduct \u2192 **conducted**\n- discuss \u2192 **discussed**\n\n---",
